@node Device_Driver_Settings "Device Driver Settings"
@{i}Device Driver Settings@{ui}

First, the name of the driver:

@{fg highlight}
  Device = scsi.device
@{fg text}

That's the one responsible for the Amiga's internal IDE or SCSI
port. Usually, multiple drives can be connected to such a port.
Therefore, we need to state which one we want:

@{fg highlight}
  Unit = 1
@{fg text}

This is the "slave" IDE drive (e.g., a ZIP drive).
The "master" harddisk has number 0.
For drivers with a single drive only, it is also 0.

@{fg highlight}
  Flags = 0
@{fg text}

Some drivers allow special settings to be made via this one.
Most cases, that 0 is enough.

@{fg highlight}
  BufMemType = 1
  MaxTransfer = 0x20000
  Mask = 0xfffffffe
@{fg text}

For the (unpatched) A1200 ROM scsi.device. Or if driver
doesn't need them, simply discard.

----------------------------------------
@{"<< Prev" link Mountlist_Configuration}  @{"Contents" link Main}  @{"Next >>" link File_System_Settings}

@endnode

@node File_System_Settings "File System Settings"
@{i}File System Settings@{ui}

@{fg highlight}
  Filesystem = l:fat95
@{fg text}

AmigaOS wants the full path here.

@{fg highlight}
  StackSize = 4096
@{fg text}

Reserve that many bytes for temporary data. State too few,
and "mysterious" crashes will happen.

@{fg highlight}
  GlobVec = -1
@{fg text}

fat95 is assembly language written, so -1.

@{fg highlight}
  Buffers = 200
@{fg text}

Hold that many blocks of 512 bytes each in memory.
More = Faster = Less memory available.

----------------------------------------
@{"<< Prev" link Device_Driver_Settings}  @{"Contents" link Main}  @{"Next >>" link Control_Options}

@endnode

@node Control_Options "Control Options"
@{i}Control Options@{ui}

@{fg highlight}
  Control = "+s"
@{fg text}

Available options:

  @{b}Option@{ub}  @{b}Description@{ub}               @{b}Default@{ub}  
  ------  ------------------------  -------  
  @{fg shine}+@{fg text}       Turn ON the following     -        
          options                            
  @{fg shine}-@{fg text}       Turn OFF the following    -        
          options                            
  @{fg shine}s@{fg text}       Force direct SCSI         OFF      
          reads/writes (for >4GB             
          disks)                             
  @{fg shine}d@{fg text}       Display extra datestamp   ON       
          info as file comments              
  @{fg shine}D@{fg text}       Record "last accessed"    ON       
          date on file reads                 
  @{fg shine}l@{fg text}       Show 8.3 filenames        OFF      
          lowercase (e.g.,                   
          "test.txt")                        
  @{fg shine}L@{fg text}       Show 8.3 filenames with   OFF      
          uppercase initial (e.g.,           
          "Test.txt")                        

----------------------------------------
@{"<< Prev" link File_System_Settings}  @{"Contents" link Main}  @{"Next >>" link Startup_Options}

@endnode

@node Startup_Options "Startup Options"
@{i}Startup Options@{ui}

@{fg highlight}
  Activate = 1
@{fg text}

Start immediately instead of on first access.

----------------------------------------
@{"<< Prev" link Control_Options}  @{"Contents" link Main}  @{"Next >>" link Partition_Selection}

@endnode

@node Partition_Selection "Partition Selection"
@{b}Partition Selection@{ub}
@{i}Subsections:@{ui}
  @{"  Automatic Partition Search (Recommended)  " link Automatic_Partition_Search__Recommended_}
  @{"  Manual Partition Definition  " link Manual_Partition_Definition}

fat95 supports both @{b}MBR@{ub} and @{b}GPT@{ub} partition tables with automatic
detection.

----------------------------------------
@{"<< Prev" link Startup_Options}  @{"Contents" link Main}  @{"Next >>" link Automatic_Partition_Search__Recommended_}

@endnode

@node Automatic_Partition_Search__Recommended_ "Automatic Partition Search (Recommended)"
@{i}Automatic Partition Search (Recommended)@{ui}

@{fg highlight}
  LowCyl = 0              /* Enable auto search */
  
  BlockSize = 512         /* Required by Mount command */
  HighCyl = 1
  BlocksPerTrack = 1
  Surfaces = 1
@{fg text}

@{b}DosType Values@{ub}

The @{b}DosType@{ub} controls which partition to mount:

  @{b}DosType@{ub}  @{b}Hex Value@{ub}   @{b}Description@{ub}            
  -------  ----------  ---------------------  
  FAT\0    0x46415400  Floppies only          
  FAT\1    0x46415401  First FAT partition    
                       (recommended)          
  FAT\2    0x46415402  Second FAT partition   
  FAT\3    0x46415403  Third FAT partition    
  FAT\4    0x46415404  Fourth FAT partition   
  FAT\5    0x46415405  First logical drive    
                       (extended partition)   
  FAT\6    0x46415406  Second logical drive,  
                       etc.                   

@{b}Recognized partition types:@{ub}

For MBR disks, fat95 recognizes these partition types:

  @{b}Type@{ub}        @{b}Description@{ub}                      
  ----------  -------------------------------  
  0x01        FAT12                            
  0x04        FAT16, < 32 MB                   
  0x06        FAT16, >= 32 MB                  
  0x0B        FAT32                            
  0x0C        FAT32, LBA                       
  0x0E        FAT16, LBA                       
  0x05, 0x0F  Extended partition (for logical  
              partitions)                      

For GPT disks, fat95 counts only FAT partitions (Microsoft Basic Data
GUID: @{fg shine}EBD0A0A2-B9E5-4433-87C0-68B6B72699C7@{fg text} ).
Non-FAT partitions (EFI System, Windows Recovery, etc.) are
automatically skipped.

@{b}GPT vs MBR Detection@{ub}

fat95 automatically detects the partition table type:
  1. Reads block 0 (MBR)
  2. Checks for protective MBR (partition type 0xEE)
  3. If found, reads GPT header at LBA 1 and scans GPT entries
  4. Otherwise, parses standard MBR partition table

----------------------------------------
@{"<< Prev" link Partition_Selection}  @{"Contents" link Main}  @{"Next >>" link Manual_Partition_Definition}

@endnode

@node Manual_Partition_Definition "Manual Partition Definition"
@{i}Manual Partition Definition@{ui}

For special cases like damaged partition tables:

@{fg highlight}
  BlockSize = 512
  DosType = 0x46415401
  
  BlocksPerTrack = 1
  Surfaces = 1
  LowCyl = <StartBlockNumber>
  HighCyl = <LastBlock>
@{fg text}

----------------------------------------
@{"<< Prev" link Automatic_Partition_Search__Recommended_}  @{"Contents" link Main}  @{"Next >>" link Mounting_the_Drive}

@endnode

