@node Special_Features "Special Features"
@{b}Special Features@{ub}

fat95 uses file comments for special commands:

@{b}Scandisk@{ub}

@{fg highlight}
  filenote CF0:anyfile "!scandisk"
@{fg text}

Recovers lost files and fixes disk errors.

@{b}Control Options@{ub}

@{fg highlight}
  filenote CF0:anyfile "!control -dD"
@{fg text}

Changes configuration options at runtime.

@{b}Security Erase@{ub}

@{fg highlight}
  filenote CF0:anyfile "!erase"
@{fg text}

Overwrites deleted files with zeroes (unrecoverable delete).
Works with CompactFlash built-in erase when available.

@{b}Note:@{ub} scandisk and erase can be aborted with @{fg shine}<ESC>@{fg text}.

----------------------------------------
@{"<< Prev" link Method_D__OS_1_3__MountList_file_}  @{"Contents" link Main}  @{"Next >>" link Troubleshooting}

@endnode

@node Troubleshooting "Troubleshooting"
@{b}Troubleshooting@{ub}
@{i}Subsections:@{ui}
  @{"  FAT32 Notes  " link FAT32_Notes}
  @{"  Disk Status Meanings  " link Disk_Status_Meanings}

@{b}Report issues at:@{ub} https://github.com/pulchart/fat95/issues

@{b}Q: "object not found" when mounting?@{ub}

A: Check the @{fg shine}Device =@{fg text}, @{fg shine}Unit =@{fg text} and @{fg shine}Flags =@{fg text} entries.

@{b}Debug tool:@{ub}

@{fg highlight}
  debug95 CF0: ram:cf0.log
@{fg text}

Creates a dump of internal fat95 variables for diagnosis.

----------------------------------------
@{"<< Prev" link Special_Features}  @{"Contents" link Main}  @{"Next >>" link FAT32_Notes}

@endnode

@node FAT32_Notes "FAT32 Notes"
@{i}FAT32 Notes@{ui}

  * FAT32 FAT table can be huge (8MB for 8GB partition)
  * fat95 does not cache entire FAT32 table to save memory
  * Free space calculation happens after mount ("volume is validating")

----------------------------------------
@{"<< Prev" link Troubleshooting}  @{"Contents" link Main}  @{"Next >>" link Disk_Status_Meanings}

@endnode

@node Disk_Status_Meanings "Disk Status Meanings"
@{i}Disk Status Meanings@{ui}

Fat95 reports different disk statuses depending on what it finds:

  @{b}Status@{ub}         @{b}ID@{ub}       @{b}Icon@{ub}               @{b}Meaning@{ub}              
  -------------  -------  -----------------  -------------------  
  @{b}Mounted@{ub}        @{fg shine}ID_DOS@{fg text}   @{fg shine}Volume name@{fg text}        FAT partition found  
                                             and mounted          
                                             successfully         
  @{b}Uninitialized@{ub}  @{fg shine}ID_NDOS@{fg text}  @{fg shine}CF0:NDOS@{fg text} or        Disk present but     
                          @{fg shine}CF0:Uninitialized@{fg text}  not FAT format       
                                             (e.g., RDB, PFS,     
                                             SFS, FFS) or bad     
                                             MBR partition table  
  @{b}No Disk@{ub}        @{fg shine}ID_NONE@{fg text}  (none)             No media inserted    
                                             OR requested         
                                             partition doesn't    
                                             exist                
  @{b}Unreadable@{ub}     @{fg shine}ID_BAD@{fg text}   @{fg shine}CF0:BAD@{fg text}            Disk read error or   
                                             hardware failure     
  @{b}Busy@{ub}           @{fg shine}ID_BUSY@{fg text}  @{fg shine}CF0:BUSY@{fg text}           Handler is           
                                             inhibited (via       
                                             @{fg shine}INHIBIT@{fg text} command)     

@{b}Partition specific behavior@{ub}

When you have multiple mount points (e.g., FAT\1, FAT\2, FAT\3) and
insert a disk:

  @{b}Scenario@{ub}          @{b}FAT\1@{ub}          @{b}FAT\2@{ub}    @{b}FAT\3@{ub}    
  ----------------  -------------  -------  -------  
  3-partition FAT   Mounted        Mounted  Mounted  
  disk                                               
  1-partition FAT   Mounted        No Disk  No Disk  
  disk                                               
  RDB/PFS/SFS disk  Uninitialized  No Disk  No Disk  
  No disk inserted  No Disk        No Disk  No Disk  

This behavior ensures:
  * @{b}FAT\1@{ub} correctly shows "Uninitialized" for foreign formats (disk present, wrong
    type)
  * @{b}FAT\2, FAT\3, etc.@{ub} correctly show "No Disk" when the requested partition
    doesn't exist

The exact status shown may depend on the order of disk insertion and
reinsertion.

----------------------------------------
@{"<< Prev" link FAT32_Notes}  @{"Contents" link Main}  @{"Next >>" link Tools_Included}

@endnode

